<div id="review_719385075" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/719385075" />
    <a title="Jamie Maltman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17852063-jamie-maltman"><img alt="Jamie Maltman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442970713p2/17852063.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/719385075?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie Maltman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie Maltman" href="/user/show/17852063-jamie-maltman">Jamie Maltman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17852063-jamie-maltman?shelf=writing">writing</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer719385075" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11284373093781293732">I almost stopped reading at the beginning, because of his liberal use of the word trash, applied to a lot of genre fiction and contemporary art and culture. But I had a gut feeling to persevere, and I&apos;m glad I did. There are indeed some very useful and important points on craft to be found in this book, as well as good exercises at the end. <br/><br/>And yes, he&apos;s a lot more nuanced in his views, and actually pushes literary-focused authors to try and make their works enjoyable and interesting on more tha</span>
  <span id="freeText11284373093781293732" style="display:none">I almost stopped reading at the beginning, because of his liberal use of the word trash, applied to a lot of genre fiction and contemporary art and culture. But I had a gut feeling to persevere, and I'm glad I did. There are indeed some very useful and important points on craft to be found in this book, as well as good exercises at the end. <br /><br />And yes, he's a lot more nuanced in his views, and actually pushes literary-focused authors to try and make their works enjoyable and interesting on more than just an intellectual level, so by the end even an aspiring genre fiction writer will respect his point of view.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11284373093781293732" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
